'''Problem:''' Let ''A'' be a square matrix. Then <math>A \to 0</math> (in operator norm) if and only if the spectral radius of <math>A < 1</math> {{HideNseek|title=Answer|text=The Spectral radius formula.}}
'''Problem:''' Let ''A'' be a square matrix. Then <math>\|A\| = \|A^*A\|^{1/2}</math>
'''Problem:''' <math>T \mapsto \sup_{\|x\|=1} (Tx \mid x)</math> is a norm for bounded operators ''T'' on a "complex" Hilbert space. {{HideNseek|title=Answer|text=It is clear that the map is a seminorm. To see it is a norm, suppose <math>(Tx \mid x) = 0</math> for all ''x''. In particular, :<math>0 = (Tx + y \mid x+y) = (Tx \mid y) + (Ty \mid x)</math> :<math>0 = (Tx + iy \mid x+ iy) = -i (Tx \mid y) + i (Ty \mid x)</math> Combing the two we get: :<math>(Tx \mid y) = 0</math> for all ''x'' and ''y''. Take <math>y = Tx</math> and we get <math>Tx = 0</math> for all ''x''.}}
